Getting TESS and Kepler light curves with lightkurve¶

TESS in a nutshell:¶

  • NASA mission launched in 2018 for continuous high-precision photometric observations
  • Field-of-view of 96 deg x 24 deg (4 cameras)
  • Starring observations of 27 days for each FOV (aka Sector)
  • The cadence of the observations is 2s but only 20s, 120s, 200s, and/or 1800s stamps are available. (2-min is the typical)
  • 13 sectors constitute a year Cycle

  • Since its launch, TESS has covered most of the sky.
  • The ecliptic has been started to be covered recently
  • A total of 97 sectors have been completed so far in its 7 years mission (Sector 98 started three days ago)

TESS light curves¶

There are several pipelines that have extracted the TESS lightcurves. The main ones are:

  • SPOC: official TESS pipeline for the selected targets with 2-min cadence (https://heasarc.gsfc.nasa.gov/docs/tess/data-handling.html)
  • TESS-SPOC: official TESS pipeline for Full Frame Images (1800s)
  • QLP: extra-official pipeline for FFIs (special detrending for finding planet transits)
  • others... (not described here)

Identifying periodicities¶

In [ ]:
# Create array of periods to search
periods = np.linspace(1, 20, 10000)
# Create a BLSPeriodogram
bls = lcsf.to_periodogram(method='bls', period=periods, frequency_factor=500);
bls.plot();
In [ ]:
# Find the peak of the periodogram:
planet_b_period = bls.period_at_max_power
planet_b_t0     = bls.transit_time_at_max_power
planet_b_dur    = bls.duration_at_max_power

# Check the value for period
planet_b_period
Out[ ]:
$3.0940094 \; \mathrm{d}$
In [ ]:
# Plot the phase-folded lightcurve on the peak periodicity:
ax = lcsf.fold(period=planet_b_period, epoch_time=planet_b_t0).scatter()
ax.set_xlim(-planet_b_period.value/2, planet_b_period.value/2);
In [ ]:
# Accessing time, flux, eflux:
time  = lcsf.time
flux  = lcsf.flux
eflux = lcsf.flux_err

Identifying stellar rotation periods:¶

In [ ]:
# Search light curve
search_result = lk.search_lightcurve('KIC 2157356', author='Kepler', quarter=(6, 7, 8))

# Download and stitch the data together
lc = search_result.download_all().stitch()

# Plot the resulting light curve
lc.plot();
In [ ]:
# Lomb-Scargle periodogram
pg = lc.to_periodogram(maximum_period=100)
pg.plot(view='period');
In [ ]:
Prot = pg.period_at_max_power
print("Your Prot is ",Prot)

Your Prot is  13.670865233376269 d

River diagrams¶

In [ ]:
lc = lk.search_lightcurve('KIC 6185476', author='Kepler', cadence='long').download_all().stitch().flatten(window_length=21)
In [ ]:
# Period (p) and and reference transit time (t0) are taken from the NASA Exoplanet Archive
p, t0 = 17.660114, 136.57258
folded_lc = lc.fold(period=p, epoch_time=t0)

# If we now plot the phase-fodled lightcurve, the transit does not clearly show up...
folded_lc.scatter();

This is because the planet is dynamically interacting with other bodies in the system and the transit is not strictly periodic.

This can be beautifully respresented in a river-plot diagram:

In [ ]:
folded_lc.plot_river(bin_points=1, method='sigma');

  • astroquery if you are using search_lightcurve() or search_targetpixelfile().
  • tesscut if you are using search_tesscut().
